> Are the only options for `-explicit` something like `true`, `false`, etc.? Should there, for example, be a way to run only explicit tests (f.e., `-explicit only`)?

I wouldn't even introduce a command line parameter, because it turns everything topsy-turvy: when a test method or class is marked `[Explicit]`, the only way to run this method or class should be by using `-class` or `-method`, as this is the explicit pendant on the CLI to the UI.  
An `-explicit` parameter would somehow water this explicitness.

> Should `-class` run explicit tests in the given class? How is this impacted by `-explicit`?  
> Should `-method` run an explicit test method? How is this impacted by `-explicit`? What about when the method is a theory, but only _some_ of the data has been marked as explicit?

It depends. Let me give some examples:
```c#
[Explicit]
public class ExplicitTests
{
    [Fact]
    public void RegularTest()
    {
    }
}

public class RegularTests
{
    [Fact]
    public void RegularTest()
    {
    }

    [Fact]
    [Explicit]
    public void ExplicitTest()
    {
    }
}
```

| Command | Result |
|-|-|
| `-class ExplicitTests` | executes `ExplicitTests.RegularTest()` |
| `-class RegularTests` | executes `RegularTests.RegularTest()`, but **not** `RegularTests.ExplicitTest()` |
| `-method RegularTests.ExplicitTest` | executes `RegularTests.ExplicitTest()` |

> [Test filtering expressions](https://github.com/xunit/xunit/issues/1833) should be part of the consideration for explicit tests (and probably match the features available via `-explicit`).

I agree. Based on the previous code sample, I'd like the following behavior:
| Command | Result |
|-|-|
| `-filter test==ExplicitTests` | executes `ExplicitTests.RegularTest()` |
| `-filter test==RegularTests` | executes `RegularTests.RegularTest()`, but **not** `RegularTests.ExplicitTest()` |
| `-filter test==RegularTests.ExplicitTest` | executes `RegularTests.ExplicitTest()` |
| `-filter category==Explicit` | executes `ExplicitTests.RegularTest()` **and** `RegularTests.ExplicitTest()` |

So in your example, you have a situation like this, right?
```c#
public class RegularTests
{
    // [Fact]
    // public void RegularTest()
    // {
    // }

    [Fact]
    [Explicit]
    public void ExplicitTest()
    {
    }
}
```

Now when running `-class RegularTests` (either from the GUI or CLI), I'd expect nothing to happen: `ExplicitTest` is explicit, so it shouldn't be executed. And since there are no non-explicit tests, that call will not run any tests. Only when executing `-method RegularTests.ExplicitTest`, a test gets executed.
